title: For Sale:  SWSA Glock dry fire trigger kit
postcontent:
I would like to offer for sale a Southwest Shooting Authority Glock dry fire trigger kit. This is a very nice kit that duplicates the Glock trigger press, weight, and reset by using real Glock parts (trigger and trigger bar, trigger mechanism housing, and connector) that have been modified to support repeated dry fire without having to rack the slide. This particular kit is matched to the stock 5.5# trigger pull.

Kit is low round count (this was my backup kit) and in excellent condition. Comes with original box and installation instructions. Installation is straightforward and can be accomplished within a few minutes, in brief, just punch out the pins and replace the entire trigger group with the dry fire trigger group.

Fits all Glock gen3 or gen4 frames except 45ACP and 10mm.

Asking $50 cash FTF.

Perfect for those Glock shooters looking for a dry fire solution that will allow them to practice multiple trigger pulls with reset. Especially helpful when ammo supply is limited or when you can't find the time to go to the range! Don't miss the opportunity to pick this kit up, supply has been limited since SWSA has become the pro shop for SHOT Ranch, and price supposedly is going up by $10 whenever they become available again.

Just so your research and don't let these people on here sell you something at way too high of a price because they paid it during the "ban scare. "

The Frame-Saver Dual Action Recoil Springs offer these advantages:

Impact: The elimination of the slide impacting the frame at high speed preserves the structure of the firearm

Muzzle Control: By changing the final backward movement of the slide from a sudden stop to a progressive stop, muzzle jump is greatly decreased by 40% giving you more control.

Function: No interference of ejection port or any feeding problems.

Progressive: This is a system designed to reduced the backward motion of the slide in progressive stages after the gun is shot. The effect of this system is that the recoil is reduced by 40% making your follow up shots much easier to shoot. This is a VERY effective system.

Stability: Better stability for your barrel. Stainless steel guide rod replaces plastic or inferior metal guide rods for superior barrel support and function.

Better Accuracy: Progressively slows down your slide from heavy impact against the frame. Works just like a car shock absorber, reducing the slide impact. Lower impact means less recoil, accurate recovery of the weapon for on-target accuracy is better achieved, shot after shot.

Lower Frame Shock: The slide is one of the heaviest components in a semi-automatic pistol. Upon firing, the slide slams back with great energy against the frame. Frame Saver Dual Actions springs can lower this slide impact dramatically, preventing excessive wear, cracked slides and damaged frames.

title: For Sale/Trade:  2008, RIA Model MAP1-FS "Tangfolio" 9mm
postcontent:
If you Like 1911's you will Love this gun. Some might mistake it for an EAA Wittness, Springfield P9, or even think it's a CZ75, and for good reason. Read Why,
------------------------------
About the Handgun:
In the 1990's the CZ75 was rapidly being undestood as one of the best combat handguns of the 20th century. Since they were made in Czech "Behind the Iron Curtain" Springfield came up with an idea to get them into the US Market. Since Italy's Tangfolio made a nearly "Perfect" Clone, Springfield started to import them under thier own label from Italy around 1990 as the P9. The Springfield P9's were rapidly turned into IPSC "Raceguns" gaining in popularity and value. Once EAA became fully vested in the US Markets with the "Witness" also made by Tangfolio, Springfield decided to pull the plug on this fine pistol in 1993.

Armscor signed a manufacturing agreement with Tanfoglio Arms of Italy to exclusively sell this pistol using the Armscor brand to its worldwide sales network.
A result of this agreement is the MAP1 pistol Assempled by Amscor in the Philippines and marketed in the US through Rock Island Armory. These Pistols use the, Reliably Proven, Browning Short Recoil Action.
-------------------------------
Now that you know a little about the history, my MAP1-FS, features a 4.45" Barrel Length, Stainless Steel - Chrome Lined Barrel, Snag Free Combat Style white-3 dot sights, Nickel Steel Alloy Frame, Black Rubber Grips, 2-16 Round Magazines, Hammer Fired - DA / SA with a Frame Mouted Abidexreus Safety, Dual Slide Cocking Serrations, Front and Rear Grip Serrations, and Durable Parkerized Finish. This is not a light weight handgun so, if you like the feel of a 1911, you will like this gun. It is an all steel gun and shoots well with little felt recoil. 
--------------------------
I value this gun at $550.00 - this is not the "New Style" Polymer Frame version but All Steel Quality.

Compare
Overview  Tech Specs  Ratings & Reviews
All The Features That Hunters Expect

The new PROSTAFF 5 3.5-14x40 features the lines mid-level magnification and several technology upgrades that will satisfy even the most demanding hunters.   A bright new optical system, remarkable hand-turn reticle adjustments with Spring-Loaded Zero-Reset turrets, and a convenient quick-focus eyepiece with a 4x zoom ratio, making adjustments while in a shooting position a breeze. The PROSTAFF 5 3.5-14x40 outfitted with the BDC reticle is an ideal fit for a variety of hunting situations and can be used with Nikon Spot On Ballistic Match Technology to take the guesswork out of compensating for bullet drop.  With enough power for the longest-range shots and a wide field of view to keep you on target even when shooting through thick brush and timber, this is one scope you can truly count on in any situation.  In addition all PROSTAFF 5 riflescopes are built with fully multicoated optics for maximum light transmission, even in extreme low light environments.
      Patented BDC Reticle
The BDC's unique see-through ballistic circles offer an incredible advantage for long range shooting, yet allow a normal sight picture for shorter-range shots where the crosshair itself is the aiming point.  The various aiming points built into the BDC reticle allows hunters to hold 'dead-on' at ranges exceeding those previously thought possible and can be utilized with Nikon’s Spot On Ballistic Match Technology to give you exact aiming points at various yardages.  Finally, you can take the guesswork out of figuring elevation and bullet drop compensation.
         Fully Multicoated Optical System
Multiple layers of anti-reflective compounds on every glass surface provide bright and vivid sight pictures and optimum light transmission and maximum brightness from dawn to dusk.
         Hand-turn 1/4 MOA Adjustments
Reticle adjustments are made in 1/4 MOA click-stop moves you can both feel and hear, and with no backlash to make your shot creep off target. Positive click reticle adjustments get you zeroed in quicker and maintain your setting—even with repeated recoil and under rugged conditions.
           Spring-Loaded Instant Zero-Reset Turrets
To simplify field adjustments, Nikon has integrated this feature into all new PROSTAFF 5 riflescopes. Just sight-in as usual, then lift the spring-loaded adjustment knob, rotate to your “zero”, and reengage. Field adjustments are now as simple as dialing-in your subsequent ranges.
        Spot On Ballistic Match Technology
Custom precision at your fingertips

The PROSTAFF 5 series, like all of Nikon’s riflescopes, are optimized for use with Nikon Spot On Ballistic Match Technology. Spot On allows you to discover all of the exact aiming points on your scope’s reticle at various yardages for your specific ammunition and load.

title: For Sale:  Rare WWII Romanian Contract Beretta M1934 .380 ACP Pistol W/2 WWII Mags
postcontent:
Rare Romanian Contract Beretta M1934 .380acp Pistol W/2 WWII Mags. Here is a Romanian contract Model 1934 Beretta military pistol assembled in 1941, as indicated by the markings on the left side of the slide, and with two original WWII Beretta magazines. The back of the right side of the frame displays Romanian armory mark, "CM". 
NO import markings!
CONDITION: Excellent, with 97-98% of original blue still on the metal. All matching serial numbers (frame, slide, barrel). Fine bore with strong and shiny rifling. Very smooth action. Difficult to find pistol without the import marks! Caliber: 9 mm Short (.380 ACP, marked on barrel). Two WWII Beretta magazines with thin metal floor plates and no other markings, both in like new condition (as is the pistol!).

This Beretta model 1934 pistol offered here was manufactured for the Romanian military in 1941. In August of 1940, the Romanian military placed a contract with Beretta for 61,000 model 1934 pistols. This contract specified that the pistols were to be delivered within seven months. The first of these pistols was not delivered until February of 1941 due to the shortage of steel and Romania's failure to send Beretta the entire fund amount for the pistols. Beginning in February of 1941, Beretta delivered 10,000 pistols with the promise of 5,000 more per month until the total contract was filled. By August of 1941, Beretta had sent a total of 40,000 pistols, but the remaining 21,000 were never delivered. This means that there are less then 40,000 of these pistols in existence today. The first of these Romanian contract pistols can be identified with a 0(zero) at the beginning of the 5 digit serial number. The Romanian contract pistols are identical to the Italian model 1934 versions except that the slide is marked 9 SCURT instead of 9mm Corto as seen in the pictures below. These Romanian model 1934 pistols were normally issued to the Romanian officers 
during WW2.

title: For Sale/Trade:  BEWARE!! WTB!!  I GOT SCAMMED ON HERE!!  READ ON PLEASE!!!
postcontent:
I got scammed by a guy who said his name was Mark Lerner.  He said his address was in Round Lake IL which checked out.  I had a WTB ad which is still up and he responded with what I needed.  He said he had what I wanted and proceeded to give me a good deal.  He said to Moneygram the money to his address in IL.  I told him from the beginning that I was weary and didn't wanna get burnt.  He re assured me and sounded like he'd sold stuff this way before.  I ended up trusting him and sent him the money.  Two days later he said he was shipping what I had purchased.  He emailed me a Fedex shipping order that looked real and had departure and arrival of package times on it.  It did not have a tracking order however.  I called Fedex and they had no history of a package being shipped from his address or one on route to mine.  I called contacted him and he said he'd call Fedex.  He re contacted me and explained that the "ATF had my package" and that "my package was almost there".  He then told me that before my package would arrive I had to pay the ATF "safe shipping fees" and to send him another Moneygram of $150.00.  Ummm... Fuck... You?  So he was persistent in trying to convince me and he played the "honesty" card well but in the end I obviously didn't send him any more money.  I'm just lucky it wasn't a $1800.00 rifle set up!!  

Call, text or email if you want any more info on this guy!  Thanks!
